      <hedline>
        <hl1>Young Doctors, Grueling Hours</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Dr Peter S Greene letter responds to June 11 news article on Accreditation Council for Graduate Medical Education's crackdown on programs that force interns and residents to work exceedingly long hours; contends long hours train doctors to make good decisions even when under stress</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Interns' Long Workdays Prompt First Crackdown'' (news article, June 11):</p>
        <p>The problem with arbitrarily limiting hours that interns or residents  must work relates to how they respond to the stresses of their profession once their training is completed. If they are trained to make good decisions only when well rested, then that is the only time they will make them.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Interns' Long Workdays Prompt First Crackdown'' (news article, June 11):</p>
        <p>The problem with arbitrarily limiting hours that interns or residents  must work relates to how they respond to the stresses of their profession once their training is completed. If they are trained to make good decisions only when well rested, then that is the only time they will make them.</p>
        <p>Interns and residents (whether they are tired or not) have senior physicians to supervise them during their training. Once they are on their own, they must know how to overcome fatigue and operate optimally without such immediate supervision. Guided experience is the only way to learn this.</p>
        <p>PETER S. GREENE, M.D.  Wilbraham, Mass., June 11, 2000</p>
      </block>
